<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="43" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
Based on the ITS phylogeny, 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. devergens" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="devergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. devergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. karelica" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="karelica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. karelica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. subdevergens" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="subdevergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. subdevergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very closely related. They are here considered as distinct species, based on the ITS phylogeny and because of a barcoding gap between the species. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nyl., Flora 55: 362" authorityYear="1872" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Verrucariaceae" genus="Verrucaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Verrucaria devergens" order="Verrucariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="devergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Verrucaria devergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically more variable than previously known (
<bibRefCitation author="Pykaelae, J" journalOrPublisher="Graphis Scripta" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" pagination="17 - 32" refId="B35" refString="Pykaelae, J, 2007. Additions to the lichen flora of Finland. II. Calcareous rocks and associated soils in Lohja. Graphis Scripta 19 (1): 17 - 32" title="Additions to the lichen flora of Finland. II. Calcareous rocks and associated soils in Lohja." volume="19" year="2007">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Pykälä">Pykaelae</normalizedToken>
2007
</bibRefCitation>
). Usually, the species has no involucrellum, but the apex of the exciple is thickened. However, specimens with an apical involucrellum, as well as two specimens in which the involucrellum covers half of the exciple, have an identical ITS sequence compared to the typical 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. devergens" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="devergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. devergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Typically, 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. devergens" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="devergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. devergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has perithecia varying from half-immersed to immersed in the same specimen, but in some specimens, the perithecia are 3/4-1-immersed, while in a few others, they are 1/4-1/2-immersed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nyl., Flora 55: 362" authorityYear="1872" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Verrucariaceae" genus="Verrucaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Verrucaria devergens" order="Verrucariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="devergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Verrucaria devergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is difficult to separate from 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. foveolata" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="foveolata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. foveolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. karelica" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="karelica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. karelica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. subdevergens" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="subdevergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. subdevergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. devergens" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="devergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. devergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. foveolata" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="foveolata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. foveolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
show similar variation in the involucrellum, i.e. absent or apical. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Massal., Ric. auton. lich. crost.: 346" authorityYear="1852" baseAuthorityName="Floerke" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Verrucariaceae" genus="Verrucaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Verrucaria foveolata" order="Verrucariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="foveolata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Verrucaria foveolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has larger spores, but there is a wide overlap in the spore size. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Massal., Ric. auton. lich. crost.: 346" authorityYear="1852" baseAuthorityName="Floerke" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Verrucariaceae" genus="Verrucaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Verrucaria foveolata" order="Verrucariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="foveolata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Verrucaria foveolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
usually has immersed perithecia, while 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. devergens" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="devergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. devergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has 1/2-1-immersed perithecia. However, some specimens of 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. devergens" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="devergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. devergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. foveolata" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="foveolata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. foveolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having 3/4-1-immersed perithecia. No consistent morphological differences were found between 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. devergens" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="devergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. devergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. karelica" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="karelica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. karelica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, although all specimens of 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. karelica" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="karelica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. karelica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have an involucrellum. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vain., Acta Soc. Fauna Flora Fenn. 49 (2): 46" authorityYear="1921" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Verrucariaceae" genus="Verrucaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Verrucaria karelica" order="Verrucariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="karelica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Verrucaria karelica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may have more often an epilithic thallus and dark lines between contiguous conspecific thalli. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pykaelae &amp; Myllys" authorityYear="2020" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Verrucariaceae" genus="Verrucaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Verrucaria subdevergens" order="Verrucariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="subdevergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Verrucaria subdevergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a longer involucrellum than 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. devergens" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="devergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. devergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in all studied specimens predominantly exceeding half of the exciple.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
Specimens of 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. devergens" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="devergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. devergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with untypically deep reaching involucrellum may be difficult to separate from 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. kuusamoensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="kuusamoensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. kuusamoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. subtilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="subtilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. subtilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pykaelae, Kantelinen &amp; Myllys" authorityYear="2020" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Verrucariaceae" genus="Verrucaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Verrucaria kuusamoensis" order="Verrucariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="kuusamoensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Verrucaria kuusamoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
tend to have a smaller exciple and shorter periphysoids, the thallus is usually epilithic and the involucrellum usually exceeds half of the exciple. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muell. Arg., Flora 57: 536" authorityYear="1874" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Verrucariaceae" genus="Verrucaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Verrucaria subtilis" order="Verrucariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="subtilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Verrucaria subtilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has thinner and smaller exciple and, on average, smaller spores. In some specimens of 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. subtilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="subtilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. subtilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, pale exciples are present, while they have never been found from 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. devergens" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="devergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. devergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
